{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775863694060,"sessionID":"ses_2864a766fffezDT0UWFUfYC9op","part":{"id":"prt_d79b97e4d001CvwLdESpK6F7VQ","messageID":"msg_d79b96b730012ZRQIj3lea5tJG","sessionID":"ses_2864a766fffezDT0UWFUfYC9op","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:47","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md","limit":100},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP Service Framework\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-004  \n6: **Module:** pkg/workloadmanager  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** M  \n9: \n10: Establish the HTTP service framework for the WorkloadManager component, providing RESTful APIs for managing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources, health endpoints, and integration with the Kubernetes client-go library.\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## Requirements\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: HTTP Server Bootstrap\n17: \n18: The system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that can be started and gracefully shut down.\n19: \n20: #### Scenario: Server starts with configuration\n21: - **GIVEN** a valid server configuration with host, port, and handler registrations\n22: - **WHEN** the operator calls `server.Start()`\n23: - **THEN** the HTTP server SHALL bind to the configured address and begin accepting connections\n24: \n25: #### Scenario: Server shuts down gracefully\n26: - **GIVEN** a running HTTP server with active connections\n27: - **WHEN** the operator calls `server.Shutdown(ctx)` with a context timeout\n28: - **THEN** the server SHALL stop accepting new connections, wait for existing requests to complete (within timeout), and release resources\n29: \n30: #### Scenario: Server configuration from environment\n31: - **GIVEN** environment variables `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_HOST` (default \"0.0.0.0\") and `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_PORT` (default \"8080\")\n32: - **WHEN** the operator initializes the server configuration\n33: - **THEN** the configuration SHALL read from these environment variables with sensible defaults\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: Server supports TLS configuration\n36: - **GIVEN** TLS certificate and key files specified in configuration\n37: - **WHEN** the operator starts the server with TLS enabled\n38: - **THEN** the server SHALL serve HTTPS using the provided certificates\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ### Requirement: Health and Readiness Endpoints\n43: \n44: The system SHALL expose standard Kubernetes health check endpoints for liveness and readiness probes.\n45: \n46: #### Scenario: Liveness endpoint returns healthy\n47: - **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager HTTP server is running\n48: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/healthz`\n49: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\": \"ok\"}` when the process is alive\n50: \n51: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint reflects dependency health\n52: - **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager has initialized all dependencies (Kubernetes client, Redis connection)\n53: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/readyz`\n54: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with body `{\"status\": \"ready\"}` when all dependencies are healthy\n55: \n56: #### Scenario: Readiness endpoint returns not ready\n57: - **GIVEN** the WorkloadManager has a failed dependency (e.g., Kubernetes API unreachable)\n58: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/readyz`\n59: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 503 with body `{\"status\": \"not_ready\", \"reason\": \"<failure_reason>\"}`\n60: \n61: #### Scenario: Health endpoint includes detailed checks\n62: - **GIVEN** the configuration enables verbose health checks\n63: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/healthz?verbose=true`\n64: - **THEN** the server SHALL return detailed health status for each registered health check component\n65: \n66: ---\n67: \n68: ### Requirement: RESTful API for AgentRuntime Resources\n69: \n70: The system SHALL expose RESTful HTTP endpoints for CRUD operations on AgentRuntime resources.\n71: \n72: #### Scenario: List AgentRuntimes\n73: - **GIVEN** AgentRuntime resources exist in namespace `default`\n74: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes`\n75: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with a JSON list of AgentRuntime objects\n76: \n77: #### Scenario: Get single AgentRuntime\n78: - **GIVEN** an AgentRuntime named `test-runtime` exists in namespace `default`\n79: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime`\n80: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 200 with the AgentRuntime JSON object\n81: \n82: #### Scenario: Get non-existent AgentRuntime returns 404\n83: - **GIVEN** no AgentRuntime named `non-existent` exists in namespace `default`\n84: - **WHEN** a GET request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/non-existent`\n85: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 404 with error details\n86: \n87: #### Scenario: Create AgentRuntime\n88: - **GIVEN** a valid AgentRuntime JSON payload\n89: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes` with the payload\n90: - **THEN** the server SHALL create the resource via Kubernetes API and return HTTP 201 with the created object\n91: \n92: #### Scenario: Create invalid AgentRuntime returns 400\n93: - **GIVEN** an invalid AgentRuntime JSON payload (missing required fields)\n94: - **WHEN** a POST request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes` with the invalid payload\n95: - **THEN** the server SHALL return HTTP 400 with validation error details\n96: \n97: #### Scenario: Update AgentRuntime\n98: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named `test-runtime`\n99: - **WHEN** a PUT request is made to `/api/v1/namespaces/default/agentruntimes/test-runtime` with updated spec\n100: - **THEN** the server SHALL update the resource and return HTTP 200 with the updated object\n\n(Showing lines 1-100 of 484. Use offset=101 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-004 — WorkloadManager HTTP Service Framework\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-004  \n**Module:** pkg/workloadmanager  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n\nEstablish the HTTP service framework for the WorkloadManager component, providing RESTful APIs for managing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources, health endpoints, and integration with the Kubernetes client-go library.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: HTTP Server Bootstrap\n\nThe system SHALL provide a configurable HTTP server that can be started and gracefully shut down.\n\n#### Scenario: Server starts with configuration","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775863694050,"end":1775863694058}}}}
